We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:
1) Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS), in accordance with Items 3.1 to 3.4 of COA Circular No. 96-011 for all the Cash in Bank accounts and submit the same to the Auditor within the timeline prescribed therein, to allow the prompt verification by the Audit Team and correction of the accounts balances in the books if any;
2) Direct the Municipal Accountant to do the following:
Adjust the noted stale checks under APPENDIX H in compliance with             Sections 59 & 61, Chapter 3, Volume I of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) for LGUs to correct the balances of the affected Cash in Bank Accounts;
Further, to correct the discrepancies noted in the Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRSs) and the long-standing reported book reconciling items listed be verified and analyzed to establish their validity and accuracy;
Should adjusting entries be made, the same shall be drawn with sufficient supporting documents. A copy of the same shall be subsequently submitted to the resident auditor for reference;
Submit to the Office of the Auditor copies of all the demand letters accordingly sent by the Municipality to the PNB and South Bank with regard to the Bank Statements and other pertinent documents being requested.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures:
Cash Shortages
1) Relieve the concerned employees with cash shortages as Accountable Officers, as required by the manual, to prevent further misapplication of government funds;
Missing Accountable Forms
2) Submit to the Audit Team copies of the related RCDs and validated deposit slips, including duplicate copies of Accountable Forms, if applicable, in case the noted missing accountable forms were already remitted and deposited;
3) Require immediate production of the said Accountable Forms noted as missing if they are still unissued;
4) Demand payment for the missing accountable forms with money value from the concerned personnel and ensure that their current collections are not used as payments;
5) Conduct an investigation to determine the status and location of the missing accountable forms and furnish the Audit Team a copy of the investigation report; and
6) Relieve the Accountable Person if he/she could not present the missing Accountable Form/s withdrawn by him/her.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:
Submit immediately the final and duly signed by the concerned Municipal officials the SCBAA and other documents particularly all the financial reports for the month of December 2024 that were not yet submitted to the Office of the Auditor;
Consider reconstruction of personnel responsibilities to ensure equitable workloads and address the agency's longstanding report submission issues;
Ensure that at least two or more office personnel are knowledgeable on report preparation in an office in order not to hamper its reportorial obligations.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:
Observation (a)
1) The Municipal Accounting Office personnel in-charge of recording deductions and processing remittances in coordination with the HRMO, shall endeavor to prepare a reconciliation schedule with supporting documents for the variances noted under Table 1 of this AAR in order to have a basis for an updated and reconciled balance.
Should adjusting entries be necessary in view of the reconciliation schedule prepared, the same shall be drawn with sufficient supporting documents. A copy of the same 	shall be subsequently submitted to the resident auditor for reference;
2) For refunds of alleged HDMF over-deductions without supporting documents enumerated in APPENDIX N of this AAR, the concerned office is to submit the following:
Copy of the payroll/s showing the amount and details of the over-deducted amount
Remittance List stamped ‘Received’ by the HDMF showing that the amount deducted was duly remitted
Certification signed by the Municipal Accountant certifying as to the existence of the over-deduction which shall include verifiable information of each refund including the amount of over-deduction, the period when the same was deducted and the amount of        over-deduction actually remitted with supporting documents
3) The office in-charge is to consider maintaining its own monitoring of loan balances of employees and check the same during computation of salaries/wages to avoid                   under/over-deductions;
Henceforth, the concerned office shall endeavor to correctly record the deductions and remittances in the books of accounts to the end that the total amount recognized as            Due to GSIS and Due to HDMF shall be the same amount recorded as remittance. Should there arise circumstances that would render the recording of deductions and remittances with variances, a reconciliation schedule shall be prepared showing the source and breakdown of the said variances;
Observation (b)
The management and the personnel in-charge should be mindful of the deadlines for remittances of GSIS and HDMF as there are imposed interests and penalties for delayed payments. More importantly, delayed remittances are detrimental to the welfare of the employees as these payments which are made on their behalf may be a cause for non-availment of certain benefits;
Should there exist interests and penalties for delayed payments, the same is to be charged to the responsible officer, in case of negligence and in no instance be charged to the Municipal funds;
Observation (c)
Submit the lacking summary lists for GSIS and HDMF remittances referred to in APPENDIX N and APPENDIX  O of this AAR;
Henceforth, ensure that GSIS and HDMF remittances are attached with summary lists and refunds are with certified copies of payroll reflecting the amounts withheld and bill statements of the concerned employees. Non-compliance with this may warrant audit suspension or disallowance, as the case may be;
Observation (d)
Prepare adjusting journal entries for personal HDMF savings and loan amortizations of JO employees recorded under the “Other General Services” account with working papers and submit the same to the audit team;
Henceforth, correctly record amounts withheld from Job Orders for GSIS and HDMF to the appropriate accounts namely, Due to GSIS and Due to HDMF/PAG-IBIG, respectively as non-adherence thereto affects the amounts stated in the Financial Statements.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures:
1) The Municipal Accounting Office personnel in-charge of recording deductions and processing remittances related to PhilHealth shall endeavor to prepare a reconciliation schedule with supporting documents for the variances noted under Table 1 of this AAR in order to have a basis for an updated and reconciled balance.
Should adjusting entries be necessary in view of the reconciliation schedule prepared, the same shall be drawn with sufficient supporting documents. A copy of the same shall be subsequently submitted to the Office of the Auditor for reference;
2) Submit as soon as possible the Statement of Premium Accounts (SPA) for the remittances covering the months of January to December 2024 in order to facilitate an effective audit of the related transactions;
3) Henceforth, the concerned office shall endeavor to correctly record the deductions and remittances in the books of accounts. Should there arise circumstances that would render the recording of deductions and remittances with variances, a reconciliation schedule shall be prepared showing the source and breakdown of the said variances;
4) Further, the concerned personnel shall see to it that all vouchers for PhilHealth remittances are attached with a printed copy of the Statement of Premium Accounts (SPA) in order to readily have a reference for the amounts being paid;
5) Prepare adjusting journal entries for personal PhilHealth premium contributions of JO employees recorded under the “Other General Services” account with working papers and submit the same to the audit team; and
6) Henceforth, correctly record amounts withheld from Job Orders for PhilHealth contributions to the appropriate account “Due to PhilHealth”, as non-adherence thereto affects the amounts stated in the Financial Statements.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:
The concerned office(s) is to prepare the required register in account of the cemetery operations which should at least show the occupied and available spaces of the Agency’s public cemetery as well as the persons who are leasing the same, in order to properly account for the correct revenue that should be due the lessees;
Considering that the agency is leasing out cemetery spaces, contemplate on issuing lease contracts or similar documents as these are vital protection against disputes and enables smooth property transactions by clearly establishing rights and details;
Review the procedures in recording revenue beginning from the Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD) up to the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher to the effect that receipts from cemetery operations are correctly classified and recorded in the proper account title to where they belong; and
Strictly adhere to the guidelines in the Local Treasurer’s Manual and the Revised Cash Examination Manual wherein collectors/tellers are required at the close of the business day to turn over all their collections intact to the liquidating officer and deposit intact all their collections, as well as collections turned over to them by sub-collectors/tellers, with authorized government depository bank (AGDB) daily or not later than the next banking day.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

1) Submit to this office a clarification and/or a justification for the utilization of LDRRM Funds for the aforementioned activities listed in Item A of this audit finding;

2) Submit the Certificates of Attendance/Appearance of the names listed in Appendix H of this report, otherwise, the same may be subjected to audit suspension/disallowance;

3) Submit to this office a clarification and/or a justification for the non-submission to the office of the Auditor of the copies of POs with five (5) days from their perfection or approval;

4) Submit to this office the lacking supporting documents of the listed disbursements in Appendix I, as applicable, otherwise, the same may be subjected to audit suspension/disallowance;

5) Refrain from using the LDRRMF for disbursements which are administrative in nature and/or do not fall within the four thematic areas of risk reduction and management laid out in Section 5 of Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 issued by the National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (NDRRMC), the Department of Budget and Management (DBM) and the Department of Interior and Local Government (DILG); and

6) Henceforth, ensure that all disbursements charged under the 5% LDRRMF and the Unexpended Balance of the LDRRMF are supported with complete and proper documents in accordance with the related rules and regulations in order to avoid audit suspensions and/or disallowances.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures:

The Municipal Budget Office and the Municipal Accounting Office shall fast track the reconciliation of the unexpended/unobligated balance of the 5% LDRRMF for CY 2023 in order to arrive at the correct amount to be recorded in the Special Trust Fund;

Draw the Journal Entry Voucher to transfer the correct amount of the CY 2023 unexpended/unobligated balance of the Quick Response Fund (QRF) and the Disaster Risk Management Fund (DRRMF)-MOOE to the Trust Liability - DRRMF Account  in the Trust Fund Books and ensure that the said amounts are to be utilized only for the purpose of supporting disaster risk reduction and management activities;

If the transfer of the CY 2023 unexpended/unobligated balance of the Quick Response Fund (QRF) and the Disaster Risk Management Fund (DRRMF)-MOOE to the Trust Liability has already been made prior to the determination of the correct amount, draw the necessary entries to correct the same;

Subsequently submit to this office the corresponding Journal Entry Voucher referred to in the two preceding recommendations. The JEV shall be supported with the appropriate and complete documents;

The Municipal Budget Office and the Municipal Accounting Office shall closely coordinate with each other to the end that the basis of the 5% LDRRMF for each year shall be consistent for both offices and that at the end of each Calendar Year, the amount of unexpended/unobligated balance to be transferred to the STF shall be reconciled in the records of both offices;

Consistently ensure that the unexpended/unobligated balance of the Quick Response Fund (QRF) and the Disaster Risk Management Fund (DRRMF)-MOOE is timely transferred to the Trust Liability - DRRMF Account in order to prevent utilization of the said funds other than for LDRRM related transactions.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures: 

Require the Municipal Treasurer to exercise due diligence in the supervision over accountable officers under her control as mandated under Section 104 of P.D. 1445 and to review the reports made by them to ensure strict compliance with the guidelines in the remittance of the collections as required under Section 307 of RA 7160, for the protection of LGU funds;

Require the Revenue Collecting Officers and Sub-collectors to remit all collections daily to the Liquidating Officer and not only once the whole stub of Official Receipt is issued;

Ensure that the remittances to the Liquidating Officer are deposited intact daily since the Depository Bank of the Municipality is just few kilometers away.

Stop the practice of the Accountable Officers of lending government funds and other forms of misappropriation as these constitute illegal use of public funds and warrant criminal action.

Require the former Liquidating Officer to settle his accountability as soon as possible.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures: 

Strictly implement the liquidation of cash advances within the prescribed period and require its full liquidation by the end of each calendar year as required by COA Circular No. 97-002;

Refrain from granting advances to officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances;

Consider administrative action for personnel with material unliquidated cash advances in prior years and require refund from those who cannot submit liquidation documents; and

Require the MACCO to prepare detailed monitoring of cash advances so as to facilitate following-up of the liquidations and to determine which check number a liquidation pertains to.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Stop the practice of granting Cash Advances without specifically stating in the “Particulars” portion of the Disbursement Voucher the specific legal purpose for which it was granted. This is to ensure that disbursements related to Cash Advances are to be granted only for a specific legal purpose as required by the related rules and regulations;

Henceforth, ensure that all disbursements pertaining to Cash Advances are supported with the required supporting documents depending on nature of the transaction as required by COA Circular No. 2023-004;

Indicate the specific legal purpose of the Cash Advances listed in Appendix M and submit the required supporting documents for each Cash Advance as required by COA Circular 2023-004 or COA Circular 2012-001, whichever is applicable.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

1) Immediately submit to the Intelligence and Confidential Fund Audit Unit (ICFAU) the liquidation of the Cash Advance for CF and/or IF granted in December 2022 under JEV No. 101-2212-3671 which is to be supported by the proper documents enumerated in Section 6.2.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 and in accordance with the submission procedures cited in Section 6.2.2.1 of the same Circular;

The Head of Agency (HoA) shall designate in writing the Special Disbursing Officer or the Head of Agency (HoA) himself as the authorized personnel to draw Cash Advances for CF and/or IF. The designated personnel shall be duly bonded and the Cash Advance drawn shall not exceed the maximum cash accountability of the SDO/HoA as indicated in his/her designation order and approved bond application. Moreover, the said personnel shall ensure compliance with Section 6.3.2 and 7.0 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 on the Responsibilities of the Special Disbursing Officer and Handling, Custody and Disposition of the Cash Disbursement Record (CDR), respectively;

The Municipal Accounting Office shall reverse the Liquidation of Cash Advances for CF and/or IF recorded in CY 2023 and shall only record the same again upon receipt of the copy of the transmittal of documents/Liquidation duly acknowledged by the ICFAU wherein the corresponding Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) shall then be submitted to the COA ATL;

Submit to this office the proper and complete supporting documents of the Cash Advance for CF and/or IF under JEV No. 101-2303-580 in accordance with Section 6.1.7 and 6.1.8.3 of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01, otherwise, the same may be subjected to Suspension or Disallowance, if warranted;

Immediately submit to this office the Disbursement Vouchers of the Cash Advances for CF and/or IF covered by JEV Nos. 101-2309-2755 (P375,000.00) and 101-2311-3434 (P375,000.00) with their corresponding proper and complete supporting documents;

Draw the necessary Journal Entry to correct the error in JEV No. 101-2311-3434 wherein the account Advances for Operating Expenses was debited instead of the account Advances to Special Disbursing Officer. Thereafter submit the corresponding JEV to the COA ATL;

The Municipal Accounting Office shall consistently ensure that the Liquidation of Cash Advances pertaining to CF and/or IF shall be recorded as such in the books of accounts only after the receipt of the copy of the transmittal of documents duly acknowledged by the ICFAU and that no additional Cash Advance for CF and/IF shall be granted unless the previous Cash Advance for the same purpose, project or activity has been duly Liquidated; and

The concerned offices and personnel shall secure a copy of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 and strictly ensure that the guidelines prescribed therein pertaining to the grant and liquidation of Cash Advances for CF and/or IF are being complied with.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Submit to this office within the prescribed period below, the lacking supporting documents of the above-listed disbursements for evaluation and verification, otherwise, the same maybe subject to Suspension or Disallowance, if warranted;

Consistently adhere to the provisions of DBM BC No. 2004-5A and the Local Government Chart of Accounts in the recognition of collections from Bid Documents and subsequent payment of Honoraria to government personnel involved in procurement activities;

Reclassify the existing balance of Other Payables - Bid Documents to the proper Trust Liabilities account.

We recommend to the management to comply with the following measures:

Submit to this office the legal basis in granting Honoraria to the listed agency personnel in view of the CBRP and the Incident Command System;

Cease the practice of granting honoraria which are the same and/or similar in nature to those subject of this report if not backed with any legal basis;

Henceforth, consistently ensure that every disbursement of the agency is supported with a legal basis and is duly supported with the required supporting documents.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Continuously improve the procurement planning process to ensure that all agency procurement are made through the modes allowed by the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

As much as practicable, refrain from making payments through reimbursement as this can be subjected to audit suspension or disallowance, if warranted, as it is not among the modes of procurement provided for by the related rules and regulations.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to use the Municipal Treasurer’s Office’s certified list of taxpayers showing the amount due for the year in setting up the Real Property Tax/Special Education Tax receivable and deferred income at the beginning of the year as required under Section 20, Volume 1 of NGAS Manual;

Draw Journal Entry Voucher to bring into harmony the aforementioned balances reflected in the Financial Statements and the Summary of Delinquent Taxes which should include the recognition of the RPT and SET Receivables from prior years. These entries shall be duly supported with working papers and documents which shall then be submitted to the Office of the Auditor for verification;

Expedite the update of data in the ETRACS and have the updated version of the software in the MTO to generate reports automatically so as not to defeat the purpose of purchasing the same;

Pending the update of the ETRACS, create mechanisms and procedures in the MTO which despite being done manually, can expedite the recording and processing of documents and reports; and

Require reconciliation between the Municipal Assessor’s Office’s Report on Real Property Assessment and the Municipal Treasurer’s Office’s certified list of taxpayers showing the amount due for the year before submitting the same to the Municipal Accounting Office as basis for setting up the RPT and SET Receivable and deferred income at the beginning of every year.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures:

Review the Other Payables account and identify all amounts which refer to fund transfers from LGUs and NGAs and prepare a schedule of the same, duly supported by Subsidiary Ledgers and certified by the Municipal Accountant which would serve as the basis for the adjusting entry to reclassify the said amounts to the account Due to LGUs, Due to NGAs or other proper accounts, whichever is applicable;

Submit to this office the Subsidiary Ledgers covering the account Other Payables under the Trust Fund wherein the total amount of the Subsidiary Ledgers should reconcile with the amount stated in the Schedule of Other Payables - Trust Fund as of December 31, 2022;

Commence the preparation of the aging schedule based on the Subsidiary Ledgers for accounts necessitating the same (e.g. Receivables and Payables) by starting gradually from the present transactions and towards earlier transactions; and

Henceforth, consistently record transactions in their proper account titles as described in the Local Government Chart of Accounts in order for the Municipality to present a fair and reliable set of financial statements for the use of various stakeholders.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures:

Pending the shift to an Electronic Accounting System, create mechanisms and procedures in the accounting office which despite being done manually, can expedite the recording and processing of documents and reports;

Henceforth, exert ample effort in submitting the Financial Statements and its
supporting schedules within the prescribed period as this has not been observed by the agency for the last six years and disregarding the same exposes the concerned officials to the repercussions provided for in the related rules and regulations;

Expedite the necessary steps to shift from manual to Electronic Accounting Systemto facilitate fast recording of transactions and timely submission of reports.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures: 

Submit an explanation with regard to the surrounding circumstances of the delay on the completion/implementation of each project shown in Annex A, indicating whether there were approved Requests for Extension for each project which exceeded the target completion date. Items which were included in the earlier reply of the BAC may be excluded; 

For those delayed projects with no approved Request for Extension, submit a copy and/or reference of the Disbursement Voucher of payments made beyond the target completion date showing that Liquidating Damages were deducted from the progress and/or final payments; 

If the supposed Liquidating Damages were not deducted to the applicable projects, apply the available remedies provided in Item 9, Annex E of RA 9184 in order to protect the interest of the government; and

More importantly, we recommend that the LGU officials consistently provide safeguards against contractors who cannot satisfactorily complete the projects on time, in order to prevent loss and wastage of government funds.

We recommended to the management to adopt the following measures: 

1) Constantly make sure that all payments for the consumption of fuel are duly supported by serially numbered and properly accomplished Trip Tickets, Requisition and Issue Voucher or Equivalent which conform to the format prescribed in the Manual on Audit for Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles, and Official Receipts/Sales Invoices/Collection Receipts for each fuel withdrawal showing the complete details such as the date, plate number of the vehicle, and kind and quantity of the fuel purchased to avoid audit suspensions or disallowances; 

2) With regard to the lacking Delivery Receipts/Charge Invoices subject of this Item 1 of this AOM, submit to this office the original DR/CI in support of the corresponding Purchase Orders where the attached DRs/CIs do not coincide with the amount in the PO; 

3) For the ensuing calendar year, the mode of procurement of fuel in accordance with the Revised IRR or RA No. 9184 should be clearly stated in the Annual Procurement Plan and any amendments thereto should be reflected in the Supplemental Procurement Plan. Such mode should be constantly followed in the purchase of fuel; 

4) Henceforth, no delivery or payment of fuel should be made prior to the execution of the Purchase Order between the Municipality and the concerned supplier to avoid uncontrolled consumption of fuel; 

5) With regard to the reimbursement of fuel consumption, abstain from continuing such practice considering that the Municipality can procure fuel through the modes provided for under RA 9184. However, for trips of long distance which would necessitate the purchase of fuel in an area far from the Municipality in view of the circumstance that the initially withdrawn fuel is not enough to cover the entire trip, reimbursement may be requested provided that the said trip has been issued a Travel Order and a Trip Ticket beforehand and all supporting documents must be attached to the request for reimbursement. Likewise, a Cash Advance in accordance with COA Circular 97-002 (Restatement with amendments of the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances provided for under COA Circular No. 90-331 dated May 3, 1990) may be requested to cover the estimated cost of additional fuel needed which should as well be supported by a Travel Order and a Trip Ticket.

We recommended to the management to adhere to the following measures:

Consistently attach to the DVs the Request for Pre-Repair Inspection (RPRI) and Waste Materials Report (WMR) and fill up all the required information especially the portion requiring the details of the Machinery and Equipment and Transportation Equipment subject of the repair and maintenance and the Mode of Disposal for those items subject to disposal. Regarding the later, if the waste materials are to be held in storage yet, indicate the same as well in the WMR;

Prior to the subsequent action thereto, ensure that all waste materials, especially those spare parts and similar items in the motorpool which does not have an enclosed area, be securely kept and/or transferred in the secure and closed storage area near the GSO to avoid loss or similar incidents prejudicial to the Municipality;

Henceforth, the GSO shall consistently keep file copies of the following forms to be used as applicable: (a) Inventory, Inspection and Appraisal of Unserviceable Property and (b) Report of Waste Materials. The said office shall ensure that any action to the unserviceable properties or waste materials are reflected int he said forms. Likewise, compliance to the procedures under COA Circular No. 92-386 shall be consistently adhered to;

With regard to the reimbursement of payment of Repairs and Maintenance, abstain from continuing such practice considering that the Municipality can undergo services and acquire goods relating to such disbursement under the modes provided for under RA 9184. Exceptional circumstances shall be dealt with as they arise and shall still be subject to existing rules and regulations.

We recommended to the management to do the following:

Justify the deviations from packed food items to giving of meal allowance in the form of cash;

Submit the Attendance Sheets bearing the original signature of the attendees duly prepared by the Barangay Secretary and confirmed by the Punong Barangay;

Justify the conduct of barangay consultations for 4 barangays was twice, instead of one (1) day activity as stated in the pertinent Activity Design.  This condition constituted unreasonable expenditure;

Submit the pertinent Program of Activity per barangay to justify the provision of 3 meals;

The Disbursing Officer should submit the payrolls duly acknowledged by payee-attendees, otherwise the unacknowledged amount remained a liability or it constituted unliquidated cash advance of the former; and

Justify the rate of meal allowances in the form of cash given to payee- attendees which was much higher compared to the rate usually given to its personnel.  Total computed amount for the difference amounted to P 331,725.00, again this constituted excessive expenditure as defined by COA Circular No. 2012-003 dated October 29, 2012.

